{
  "texts": [
    "They set (a sad face) as their own avatar and (an angry face) as the chatbot avatar, hoping for an empathetic and fiery response, such as \"if he keeps wanting to fight, we'll fight to the end!\"",
    "P2 shared a similar practice: they once assigned (red heart) to their own avatar and chose the (face blowing a kiss) for the chatbot who played \"a friend who chats with me to kill time.\"",
    "When asked whether they intentionally matched these two avatars, they said: \"Yes, and I mainly use the emojis with hearts (for both of us).\"",
    "They further explained that pairing these heart-themed avatars created a sense that the conversation was \"consistently warm and friendly\".In other cases, participants may focus on expressing their own feelings by choosing an avatar for themselves without choosing an avatar for the chatbot.",
    "For example, P4 reported they often chose (grinning face) when they felt good and (crying face) when they felt down."
